---

## 1. What this is

Slow Burn OS is a personal operating system — a mobile-first PWA designed to help people take control of their own metrics of growth. It is not a productivity app. It is not a wellness app. It is a tool for people who do a lot, measure themselves against someone else's standards, and have lost track of what actually matters to them.

**The core belief:** You don't need to do more. You need to know what's worth doing — and measure that instead.

**Tagline:** Count what counts.

**Subtitle:** Your life. Your metrics.

---

## 2. Who it's for

This app is for people who are burning out — not because they do too little, but because they do too much, and none of it is measured on their own terms.

- **The housewife or working mother** who runs a household, manages children, holds a job — and hasn't done something purely for herself in months. Everything she does is for someone else's benefit.

- **The corporate professional** whose entire sense of progress is defined by someone else's KPIs. They're performing well by the company's metrics but have no idea what their own metrics would be.

- **The person working on autopilot** from morning to evening. All their tasks have gone from automatic to unconscious. They're productive but it's eating them alive and they can't name why.

- **Anyone under societal pressure** to be a certain way — who needs a space to define their own terms.

**The common thread:** These people are strong, capable, and busy. They are not fragile. They are lost in other people's definitions of what matters. The app's job is to be a mirror, not a crutch.

---

## 3. Product philosophy

### 3.1 Core principles

**Start small.** The app gently guides people to begin with two or three categories, not six. Adding more should feel like growth, not setup.

**Your metrics, not theirs.** Every metric in the app is self-defined. No external benchmarks, no leaderboards, no comparison. Progress is measured against your own terms.

**The smallest thing is a win.** Completing one non-negotiable should feel meaningful, not like the minimum. The app never implies you should be doing more.

**Prodding, not pushing.** The app is helpful in a non-invasive, no-pressure way. It prods gently. It does not nag, streak-shame, or gamify compliance.

**Confront, then support.** The app asks a hard question — what truly matters to you? — and then makes it easy to act on the answer. The confrontation is in the framing. The support is in the daily experience.

### 3.2 What this is NOT

- Not a productivity app — no optimization, no efficiency metrics, no hustle
- Not a habit tracker — no streaks to protect, no punishment for missing a day
- Not a therapy app — it does not diagnose, treat, or counsel. It is a mirror, not a doctor
- Not a social app — no sharing, no comparison, no community features in V1 or V2

---

## 4. Version plan

| Version | Name | Storage | Status |
|---------|------|---------|--------|
| V1 | Lite | localStorage only | Prototype complete |
| V2 | Full | Supabase (cloud sync) | Architecture designed, not built |

V1 is the reader-facing version: localStorage only, no auth, no backend. Its purpose is to be usable and shareable while the content narrative (Substack articles) is published.

V2 adds persistence via Supabase so data survives browser clears, syncs across devices, and enables features like year-end reports.

---

## 5. App architecture

### 5.1 Two parallel systems

The app runs two systems that work together but stay separate:

**Non-negotiables (NNs)** — Daily anchors tied to life categories (body, mind, spirit, etc.). These are about showing up for yourself today. They do not connect to goals. They appear in the Today view only.

**Goals + Tasks** — Longer-term direction. Tasks flow from the Dump into the Week Ahead, get tagged to goals, and completion data feeds the Mirror. This is about where you're going.

### 5.2 Four views

| View | Name | Purpose | Time direction |
|------|------|---------|----------------|
| Today | Today | NNs + today's tasks with goal alignment | Present |
| Dump | Dump | Brain dump inbox — zero friction | Timeless |
| Plan | The Week Ahead | Sprint plan: assign to days, tag to goals | Forward 7 days |
| Mirror | Mirror | Goal alignment data + weekly reflection | Backward 7 days |

### 5.3 Data flow

The lifecycle of a task:

1. User brain dumps a thought into the Dump. It's raw text, nothing else.
2. During weekly planning (The Week Ahead), user pulls tasks from Dump. They assign a day (Sun–Sat) and tag to one or more goals (or leave untagged). Optionally add estimated duration.
3. When the assigned day arrives, the task appears in Today alongside non-negotiables.
4. User completes the task (optionally logging actual duration). It moves to "done."
5. At week end, Mirror shows: how many tasks were goal-aligned vs. untagged. Time invested per goal (if durations were logged). Weekly reflection prompt.
6. Unfinished tasks roll back to Dump. No guilt, no red flags. Just back in the inbox.

**Week starts on Sunday.** Plan when your mind is quieter.

---

## 6. Non-negotiable categories

| ID | Label | Icon | Default non-negotiable |
|----|-------|------|----------------------|
| body | Body | 🏃 | Morning movement |
| mind | Mind | 🧠 | Deep work block |
| spirit | Spirit | 🕯️ | Morning stillness |
| people | People | 🤝 | Connect with someone I love |
| growth | Growth | 🌱 | Work on my craft |
| rest | Rest | 🌙 | Evening wind-down |

Users select 1–6 categories during onboarding and write their own non-negotiable labels. Everything is editable in Settings.

---

## 7. Goals

Users set personal goals during onboarding. Goals are the spine of the app — tasks get tagged to them, and the Mirror shows how time aligns with intention.

**Recommended: 3 goals. Maximum: 5.** Backed by behavioral research: multiple goals competing for the same resources (time, attention, energy) decrease performance. Three gives enough range without cognitive overload.

### Goal setup — three guided prompts:

1. **"What's the goal?"** — title (e.g. "Launch my Substack")
2. **"How will you know you've done it?"** — measurable outcome (e.g. "4 posts published, 100 subscribers")
3. **"By when?"** — target date

This gets Specific, Measurable, and Time-bound without saying "SMART." Human language, not corporate.

### Goal colour palette (auto-assigned):

| Goal 1 | Goal 2 | Goal 3 | Goal 4 | Goal 5 |
|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
| #5A856B Sage green | #7B8AB5 Dusty blue | #B5885A Warm clay | #8B6B8A Muted plum | #5A8A8A Quiet teal |

Untagged tasks use #C4BBAF, labelled "Other things" in the Mirror.

---

## 8. Task-goal tagging

**Strongly encouraged, not mandatory.**

When moving a task from Dump to the Week Ahead, the planning modal prominently shows goal tags with the prompt: *"Is this for a goal?"*

If nothing is selected, a gentle nudge appears: *"Tag it to a goal — or mark it as 'other.' This is how you see where your time goes."*

"Not for a goal" is an explicit button with its own grey dot. But the user can still plan without choosing — not blocked.

**A task can be tagged to multiple goals.** Reflects reality — "Write Substack post" could serve both a growth goal and a career goal.

**Goal alignment is visible everywhere:**
- Every task shows goal colour dot(s) or grey "other" dot in all views
- Today view includes a goal alignment indicator: "3 of 5 for your goals"
- Mirror shows the full weekly breakdown

---

## 9. Duration tracking

Tasks have two optional duration fields:

- **Estimated duration** — set when planning (quick-select: 15m, 30m, 1h, 2h, or custom)
- **Actual duration** — logged on completion

Both are optional. Some users want deep tracking. Others just want to check things off. Both are valid. When logged, duration data feeds the Mirror's time-per-goal breakdown.

---

## 10. Onboarding

### 10.1 Flow

**Screen 1:** "Count what counts." / "Your life. Your metrics." — the phrase, the brand, a Begin button. Full screen, let it breathe.

**Screen 2:** Interactive tour — four slides showing each tab with a mockup and one-line description. Skip button always visible.

- Today: *"Your day starts here. Check off your non-negotiables and see what's planned."*
- Dump: *"Brain full? Dump it here. No structure needed — just get it out."*
- The Week Ahead: *"Plan your week. Every task gets tagged — is it for your goals, or for everything else?"*
- Mirror: *"See where your time actually went. Not as judgement — as clarity."*

**Screen 3:** Non-negotiable categories. "Where do you want to show up?" All six visible, guide toward 2–3. For each selected category, user writes their NN label: *"What's one thing in this area that's just for you?"*

**Screen 4:** Goals. "Now, where do you want to go?" Three guided prompts per goal. Gentle note: *"Most people start with 2 or 3."*

### 10.2 Tour re-showing

- First use: auto-shown during onboarding
- Visits 2–5: banner prompt: "Need a refresher on how things work?"
- After that: available via Settings ("Replay tour")

---

## 11. Design direction

### 11.1 Visual direction

Light palette. Inspired by the warmth of Headspace and the calm of the Calm app, but distinct from both.

**Emotional register:** "The first ten minutes after you wake up when the light is soft and nothing has gone wrong yet." Muted tones, generous spacing, unhurried.

### 11.2 Colour tokens

| Token | Value | Usage |
|-------|-------|-------|
| bg | #F6F2EC | Main background — warm linen |
| card | #FFFFFF | Card/surface background |
| cardDone | #F2F6F3 | Completed item background |
| border | #E6E0D6 | Default borders |
| borderDone | #C4D8CC | Completed item border |
| accent | #5A856B | Primary accent — sage green |
| accentSoft | rgba(90,133,107,0.08) | Accent background fill |
| text | #2A2622 | Primary text |
| textSoft | #736D64 | Secondary text |
| textMuted | #B0A99E | Placeholder/meta text |

### 11.3 Typography

- **Primary font:** Newsreader (serif), fallback Georgia. The app is a reflective tool, not a SaaS dashboard.
- **Meta font:** DM Sans (sans-serif) for labels, tab names, system text.
- **Max width:** 430px. Mobile-first. No desktop layout in V1.
- **Sizes:** 28px headings, 16px body/tasks, 12px labels, 11px meta.

### 11.4 Interaction patterns

- All transitions: 0.35s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1) — unhurried
- Tap targets: minimum 44px
- Completion feedback: soft background colour shift + checkmark. No confetti, no streaks.
- Empty states: always warm, never imply failure

### 11.5 Tone of voice

The app's voice is direct, warm, and never performative. It names what happened and trusts the user to feel it.

| State | Copy |
|-------|------|
| Zero NNs done | "These are yours. Not anyone else's." |
| Partial NNs | "[n] of [total]. Your pace, your terms." |
| All NNs done | "You showed up for yourself today." |
| All-done message | "Small steps still move you forward." |
| Empty dump | "Your mind is clear. For now." |
| No tasks today | "Nothing planned for today. That's okay too." |
| Empty mirror | "No completed tasks this week yet." |

---

## 12. Settings

Accessible from gear icon, full-screen overlay.

**Editable in V1:**
- Non-negotiable labels (per category)
- Add or remove categories (1–6)
- Edit goals: title, measure, target date, mark completed/paused
- Add new goals (up to 5 active)
- Replay tour
- Start Over: clears all data, returns to onboarding (requires confirmation)

**Not editable in V1:**
- Week start day (fixed: Sunday)
- Goal colour assignments (auto-assigned)
- Export/import data (V2)

---

## 13. Decisions log

| Date | Decision | Options considered | Rationale |
|------|----------|-------------------|-----------|
| Mar 12 | Light palette over dark | Dark, Light, Both | Dark felt too intense. Light matches "quiet space for self-definition." |
| Mar 12 | Sage green accent over gold | Gold (#B48C64), Sage (#5A856B) | Gold carries ambition energy. Sage says growth without pressure. |
| Mar 12 | Onboarding phrase: "Count what counts" | Track what's yours, Define the scorecard, Count what counts, Not everything counts, Measure yours | Rhythmic, memorable, distinct from Doerr's "Measure What Matters." |
| Mar 12 | Name stays: Slow Burn OS | Keep, Reconsider | "Slow burn" captures building back gradually. Not intensity — endurance. |
| Mar 12 | Target user reframed | Fragile/recovery vs. strong-but-lost | Not for people who can't get out of bed. For people who haven't stopped moving. |
| Mar 21 | Subtitle: "Your life. Your metrics." | "A personal OS for people who do a lot...", "Your life. Your metrics." | Original was too on the nose — diagnosed the user. New version is an invitation. |
| Mar 21 | Screen 2 becomes interactive tour | Framing statement, Tour, Video | Users don't need more poetry after the hook. They need to know how to use it. |
| Mar 21 | Categories first, then goals | Goals first, Categories first | NNs are about today. Goals are about direction. Ground in present first. |
| Mar 21 | Three guided goal prompts | Single SMART field, Three prompts | Gets S/M/T without saying SMART. Human language, not corporate. |
| Mar 21 | Tagging strongly encouraged, not mandatory | Mandatory, Encouraged, Optional | Forcing the choice is the philosophy, but blocking creates abandonment risk. |
| Mar 21 | Multiple goals per task | One goal, Multiple, Primary + secondary | Reflects reality. Some tasks serve more than one goal. |
| Mar 21 | Estimated + actual duration, both optional | Required, Optional, No tracking | Serves deep trackers without punishing light users. |
| Mar 21 | Week starts Sunday | Monday, Sunday, User choice | Plan when your mind is quieter. |
| Mar 21 | 3 goals recommended, max 5 | 1–3, Up to 5, No limit | Behavioral research: competing goals decrease performance. 3 is the sweet spot. |
| Mar 21 | Four views (Today, Dump, Plan, Mirror) | Original six tabs | Simplified. Every view has a clear job. Board is implicit in the flow. |
| Mar 21 | Unfinished tasks roll back to Dump | Stay planned, Delete, Roll back | No guilt. Just back in the inbox. |

